		<td width="150" align="left" valign="top" class="row1"><span class="name"><a name="83598"></a><b>Balanz son of Anz</b></span><br /><span class="postdetails">Wielder of the BanHammer of Oppression<br /><br /><br />Joined: 30 Nov 2000<br />Posts: 1194<br /></span><br /></td>
		<td class="row1" width="100%" height="28" valign="top"><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
			<tr>
				<td width="100%"><a href="viewtopic.php?p=83598&amp;sid=fa8498249091bd9824bfdf6c2237f866#83598"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails">Posted: Sun Sep 07, 2003 7:13 pm<span class="gen">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;Post subject: Anti-Summon Shield: Alternative to Concussion?</span></td>
				<td valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><a href="posting.php?mode=quote&amp;p=83598&amp;sid=fa8498249091bd9824bfdf6c2237f866"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/lang_english/icon_quote.gif" alt="Reply with quote" title="Reply with quote" border="0" /></a>   </td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">As a <span style="font-style: italic">Strict Class Separatist</span>, I am strongly opposed to giving mages additional direct effects against enemies, such as concussion, snare, root, slow, stun, and so on.  The opposing school I call <span style="font-style: italic">Accretionists</span>, who do not think class distinctions are that important, and see little wrong with mages acquiring the simplest, most direct tools for the job.
<br />

<br />
It is pretty clear that in some raids, especially in the endgame, mages are crippled by a lack of aggro management.  Besides the problems with pets, which <span style="font-style: italic">LDoN</span> is said to address at least somewhat, raiding mages are sub-par damage dealers because they are aggro limited.  For this reason, several senior raiding mages have suggested that mages should get some form of direct concussion, either as a spell or an end-game dropped right-click, rather like the wizard pants.
<br />

<br />
However, the problem is not necessarily aggro <span style="font-style: italic">per se</span>, but rather the <span style="text-decoration: underline">consequences</span> of aggro, i.e. getting summoned and if not squashed like a bug, slapped around silly and unable to safely cast spells.
<br />

<br />
Therefore, I propose we consider an old idea that never came to life, namely, a self-only <span style="font-style: italic">Anti-Summoning Shield</span> for mages.
<br />

<br />
My initial idea is that this would act something like a rune, and would prevent the mage from being summoned.  Doing so would kill the rune, and at the same time, significantly reduce the mage's position on the hate list, rather like <span style="font-style: italic">Concussion</span> or <span style="font-style: italic">Feign Death</span>.  The mage would then have to recast the shield, and could then resume nuking.
<br />

<br />
It seems to me that this could solve the mage aggro management problem in a manner consistant with current mage abilities, and without simply borrowing effects from other classes.  It would be distinctly magely, and might close a significant chunk of the mage raid damage gap.
<br />

<br />
To quote <span style="font-style: italic">Absor</span> in response to questions in this very forum:
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-style: italic"><span style="font-weight: bold">"Mages should be respected damage dealers,"</span></span>
<br />

<br />
and yet raiding guilds actively seek wizards over mages by about a factor of ten to one, as evidenced by the various guild recruitment web pages.  If mages were considered <span style="font-style: italic">"respected damage dealers,"</span> they should be an adequate subsitute for wizards on raids, but clearly they are not.
<br />

<br />
While mages have never had rune spells themselves, there are several mage equipable items that have rune effects, for example <span style="font-style: italic">Orb of Lost Souls</span>.  Putting an <span style="font-style: italic">Anti-Summoning Shield</span> as an effect on a raid drop could address the problem while not overpowering non-raid mages.  It would also be relatively easy to implement in game.
<br />

<br />
Is this a viable means of addressing the mage raid damage gap?
<br />
How good would it have to be, i.e. how much hate would it have to drop?  All of it, like <span style="font-style: italic">Feign Death</span>, or half of it?  A fixed amount like <span style="font-style: italic">Concussion</span>?
<br />
Would it overpower raid mages when they are solo or grouped?
<br />
How good would it have to be to be <span style="font-style: italic">"too good?"</span>
<br />

<br />
I look forward to your thoughtful responses, especially those of our most senior mages who are experienced in that part of the game.  At the same time, I invite less senior mages to comment, as it possible that the mage raid damage gap occurs before the end game for mages without the best equipment and not in the best guild.  Such mages also deserve a place besides wizards, if the gap exists for them also.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Razamatazz Pizzazz</span></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
