			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Shazar wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Now you're talking runes, concussion and feign death effects. Not exactly class separatist talk in my book.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">The specific principle I employ here is:
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-style: italic"><span style="font-weight: bold">"Mages may only directly effect their foes through three means: elementals, fire and magic damage spells, and the malise line of spells."</span></span>
<br />

<br />
The <span style="font-style: italic">Anti-Summon Shield</span> is still a nebulous idea, but is more consistant with mage abilities, and was previously proposed <span style="text-decoration: underline">by Sony</span> for mages.  Mages are already able to cast right-click runes like <span style="font-style: italic">Shield of Auras</span> and <span style="font-style: italic">Orb of Lost Souls</span>.  Given the problem this is intended to solve, the <span style="font-style: italic">Anti-Summon Shield</span> would probably also be a right-click, and not a memorized spell.
<br />

<br />
And how could we possibly discuss an anti-summoning shield <span style="text-decoration: underline">without</span> comparing it to <span style="font-style: italic">Concussion</span> and <span style="font-style: italic">Feign Death</span>?  The anti-summon shield is intended to fulfill literally the same role as these two abilities, that is, giving a caster class a means of managing their position on the hate list.  Further, the anti-summon shield cannot be better than either of these two abilities, else it would be unbalancing.  Thus, <span style="font-style: italic">Concussion</span> and <span style="font-style: italic">Feign Death</span> form strong upper limits to the efficacy of the <span style="font-style: italic">Anti-Summon Shield</span>.
<br />

<br />
Thus, for example, when it was suggested that the shield could be abused for aggro kiting, I suggested that the shield root the caster in place.
<br />

<br />
The anti-summon shield, in its current vague form, would have disadvantages compared to concussion.  It is still essentially passive, and is not targetted against a specific mob.  Thus, for example, an unexpected add may pop the anti-summon shield instead of the mob intended.  The anti-summon shield is all or nothing: it cannot be used to carefully adjust one's position on the hate list the way concussion can.  The mage cannot control <span style="text-decoration: underline">when</span> it takes effect, unlike concussion or feign death.
<br />

<br />
Like <span style="font-style: italic">Feign Death</span>, the anti-summon shield would hold the caster in place, not allowing them to move.  But unlike feign death, the mage would be immobile the entire time <span style="text-decoration: underline">before</span> hate reduction took place.  On the other hand, the mage can cast spells while fixed in place.  <span style="font-style: italic">Feign Death</span> adjusts the caster's position on <span style="text-decoration: underline">all</span> hate lists, while the anti-summon shield only adjusts the hate list of the mob that pops the shield.
<br />

<br />
Like <span style="font-style: italic">Concussion</span>, the anti-summon shield would serve to keep the caster from being summoned, and reduce the caster's position on the hate list.  However, unlike concussion, the shield would not allow the mage to actively manage his hate.  Indeed, the mage cannot even be certain <span style="text-decoration: underline">which</span> mob's hate will be reduced!
<br />

<br />
And rather than simply imitating <span style="font-style: italic">Concussion</span> or <span style="font-style: italic">Feign Death</span>, abilities of classes whose distinctions are already far too blurry for my taste, the anti-summon shield creates a distinct new ability, with its own trade-offs and tactics.  It is, in my opinion, distinctly magely.</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Kaen wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">a summons aggro reduction item would be nice... other classes could use it as well tho.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">The problem is that if it helps wizards, it does little or nothing the close the gap.  That is why I suggest that the anti-summon shield be self-only.  We need something to improve <span style="text-decoration: underline">mage</span> raid damage output.</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Scrawl wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Great idea Balanz.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">Although I couldn't tell you the authors of this idea, it is <span style="text-decoration: underline">not</span> mine.  All I have done is extract the ideas of other people and put them together in a coherent form.  I am responsible for the specific version I have proposed, but the idea has long been latent in the forum in various threads in the last couple years.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Razamatazz Pizzazz</span>
<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">"Jez doin' ma job, ma'am."</span></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
