			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">The old style AntiSummoned Shield that was on Test and looking at going live was an AoE style effect similar to Sanctuary (that stupid sentinel spell). It affected the area, and anyone that stayed within it was immune to summoning. Of course, there was a problem with the aggro. Just because the mob couldn't summon the target didn't mean it wouldn't still be on top of the hate list. The mob would charge the person it hated, hidden int he Anti Summoned Shield, and all positioning was destroyed. In a way, it's good it didn't go live, because it would've caused more problems than not.
<br />

<br />
The method of aggro control that Balanz is proposing is actually good. It's unique, let's magicians nuke til summon, then disrupts it so that the hate drops significantly. Only problems i see: What happens if the mob doesn't summon, or if it just summoned someone else? It will not control your aggro, and the mob will chase you down and kill you in melee, rather than bringing you to it.
<br />

<br />
Something to consider.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
