			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I think the trigger for popping the shield would have to be whenever a mob decided either that they should summon the mage, or else take a step towards the mage.  At that point the shield pops, and the mage moves down that mob's hate list.
<br />

<br />
How far down the hate list?  I see two obvious possibilities.
<br />

<br />
It coud act similarly to <span style="font-style: italic">Feign Death</span> and drop the mage's hate to a <span style="text-decoration: underline">ction</span> ts former value.  If that fraction were zero, it would be very similar to feign death and probably too good.  If it were much worse than two-thirds, it might be almost useless.
<br />

<br />
Alternately, it could act like <span style="font-style: italic">Concussion</span> and reduce the mage's hate by a fixed amount.  This has the advantage of being easier to analyze, since we can compare it to concussion, and determine a reasonable value.
<br />

<br />
For those who suggest that this ability would be <span style="font-style: italic">"over-powering,"</span> I ask you to be clear about under what circumstances.  Give specific scenarios.  This will illuminate possible limits and balances to the ability.
<br />

<br />
For example, the notion that a simple shield would make aggro kiting too good.
<br />

<br />
As for making wizards angry, I think as long as we close the mage raid damage gap, but do not eliminate it, so that mages are adequate substitutes for wizards, but wizards are still prefered, then wizards should have little to complain about.
<br />

<br />
What <span style="text-decoration: underline">are</span> <span style="font-style: italic">"respected damage dealers"</span> <span style="text-decoration: underline">supposed</span> to do on a raid, except mostly deal damage?  And if wizards, and maybe rogues and rangers, have that role completely sewn up, what is the point of being a raiding mage?
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Raz</span></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
